WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.800 --> 00:00:02.933
Male describer: A MULTIMEDIA
SLIDE PRESENTATION IS TITLED

00:00:02.933 --> 00:00:07.333
"HTML5 VIDEO ACCESSIBILITY
AND THE WebVTT FILE FORMAT.

00:00:07.333 --> 00:00:10.700
MARCH 23, 2011.
SILVIA PFEIFFER."

00:00:10.700 --> 00:00:13.600
IN AN AUDITORIUM,
A WOMAN SPEAKS AT A PODIUM.

00:00:13.600 --> 00:00:16.133
Black: So welcome all.
Thank you for coming.

00:00:16.133 --> 00:00:17.500
My name is Naomi Black,

00:00:17.500 --> 00:00:19.500
and I'm a member of the
Accessibility Engineering Group

00:00:19.500 --> 00:00:20.666
here at Google.

00:00:20.666 --> 00:00:22.266
And today,
I'm very pleased to invite

00:00:22.266 --> 00:00:24.400
our speaker,
Dr. Silvia Pfeiffer.

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:27.733
Silvia is a member
and an invited expert

00:00:27.733 --> 00:00:31.333
on the W3C HTML
Accessibility Task Force.

00:00:31.333 --> 00:00:33.200
And she's also
the author of

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:35.833
"The Definitive Guide
to HTML5 Video."

00:00:35.833 --> 00:00:37.500
So Silvia's here
to talk to us--

00:00:37.500 --> 00:00:38.833
come on up.

00:00:38.833 --> 00:00:41.533
Silvia's here to talk to us
today about WebVTT,

00:00:41.533 --> 00:00:43.500
which is one of the standards
for timed text

00:00:43.500 --> 00:00:45.433
which is under consideration
by the W3C.

00:00:45.433 --> 00:00:46.566
Thank you, Silvia.

00:00:46.566 --> 00:00:47.600
Pfeiffer: Thank you.

00:00:47.600 --> 00:00:49.166
Describer:
SILVIA TAKES THE PODIUM.

00:00:49.166 --> 00:00:50.966
Pfeiffer: Thanks for inviting me
to come and speak

00:00:50.966 --> 00:00:53.333
about this
important topic today.

00:00:53.333 --> 00:00:55.633
We know there are a lot
of discussions going on

00:00:55.633 --> 00:00:59.066
about formats
for captions,

00:00:59.066 --> 00:01:01.500
and we want to standardize them
for the web.

00:01:01.500 --> 00:01:03.566
But standardizing it
for the web

00:01:03.566 --> 00:01:05.166
has a much larger
impact these days

00:01:05.166 --> 00:01:06.833
than just on web browsers,

00:01:06.833 --> 00:01:08.033
just on the web itself.

00:01:08.033 --> 00:01:09.766
It goes into many
different devices.

00:01:09.766 --> 00:01:12.366
So we're very interested
and very keen

00:01:12.366 --> 00:01:15.866
to give a broad coverage
of available technology,

00:01:15.866 --> 00:01:18.033
and this is what we're trying
to do here today.

00:01:18.033 --> 00:01:24.600
So I'll be talking mostly about
WebVTT, the file format.

00:01:24.600 --> 00:01:26.866
But I'll also be talking
a little bit about

00:01:26.866 --> 00:01:31.200
how to plug that into
the web browser into HTML

00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:32.866
so that in the future,

00:01:32.866 --> 00:01:36.333
we have a very simple way
of displaying captions

00:01:36.333 --> 00:01:39.066
in web browsers on videos

00:01:39.066 --> 00:01:41.966
without having to do
much more than authoring a file

00:01:41.966 --> 00:01:46.200
and giving a link to
the web browser for that file.

00:01:46.200 --> 00:01:48.633
So it will be very simple
for people in the future

00:01:48.633 --> 00:01:50.100
to create more captions.

00:01:50.100 --> 00:01:52.400
Describer: SYLVIA CUES
A NEW SLIDE TITLED

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:54.400
"REQUIREMENTS
OF A WEB TEXT FORMAT."

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:57.066
HEADINGS BELOW READ
"CAPTIONS OR SUBTITLES"

00:01:57.066 --> 00:02:00.133
"TEXT VIDEO DESCRIPTIONS"
"NAVIGATION OR CHAPTERS"

00:02:00.133 --> 00:02:01.666
AND "METADATA."

00:02:01.666 --> 00:02:03.333
Pfeiffer: All right,
let's dig right in.

00:02:03.333 --> 00:02:06.233
As we were looking
at requirements

00:02:06.233 --> 00:02:08.166
of such a text format,

00:02:08.166 --> 00:02:10.866
a web text format
for video,

00:02:10.866 --> 00:02:14.933
we looked at the different
types of content

00:02:14.933 --> 00:02:18.133
that can be time-aligned
with video.

00:02:18.133 --> 00:02:20.766
And captions and subtitles
are the obvious ones,

00:02:20.766 --> 00:02:24.866
but text video descriptions
are also an important use.

00:02:24.866 --> 00:02:26.866
These are for blind users

00:02:26.866 --> 00:02:29.500
and can be read out
by screen readers

00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:33.133
in parallel to the playback
of the video.

00:02:33.133 --> 00:02:37.266
This may well not be
the most usable way

00:02:37.266 --> 00:02:38.866
of doing
audio descriptions,

00:02:38.866 --> 00:02:40.933
but it is a much easier
way to publish

00:02:40.933 --> 00:02:44.766
audio descriptions
for blind users.

00:02:44.766 --> 00:02:46.466
And, in fact,
for a lot of blind users,

00:02:46.466 --> 00:02:48.633
it may well be
all they need,

00:02:48.633 --> 00:02:51.133
because they already have
their screen readers set up,

00:02:51.133 --> 00:02:54.533
and it works really well
for some people.

00:02:54.533 --> 00:02:55.900
Further to that,

00:02:55.900 --> 00:02:58.833
we're also talking about
navigation or chapters,

00:02:58.833 --> 00:03:01.066
which is also
very important

00:03:01.066 --> 00:03:04.766
for blind and,
in fact, any user.

00:03:04.766 --> 00:03:07.033
If you want to go through
a video quickly

00:03:07.033 --> 00:03:08.466
and find out
what's in there,

00:03:08.466 --> 00:03:13.500
you want to jump to what we now
know as chapter markers.

00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:15.100
We can call them
navigation markers.

00:03:15.100 --> 00:03:19.300
This can be also covered
with the same kind of format.

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:22.366
And more generally,
metadata.

00:03:22.366 --> 00:03:24.100
This is something
that archives

00:03:24.100 --> 00:03:26.100
are particularly
interested in,

00:03:26.100 --> 00:03:29.666
to attach metadata
to sections in the video.

00:03:29.666 --> 00:03:33.000
It can also be done with such
a time-aligned text format.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.800
So what we have
discussed for browsers

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:38.366
is a very simple format.

00:03:38.366 --> 00:03:41.966
It's called WebVTT,
Video Text Tracks.

00:03:41.966 --> 00:03:43.966
WebVTT.

00:03:43.966 --> 00:03:47.866
Describer: A NEW SLIDE TITLED
"WebVTT OR VIDEO TEXT TRACKS."

00:03:47.866 --> 00:03:51.700
A SAMPLE FILE IS HEADED "WEBVTT"
WITH TWO ELEMENTS BELOW.

00:03:51.700 --> 00:03:54.366
EACH ELEMENT CONTAINS
THREE LINES OF INFORMATION:

00:03:54.366 --> 00:03:55.633
CAPTION NUMBER,

00:03:55.633 --> 00:03:57.300
TIME CODE START
AND TIME CODE END,

00:03:57.300 --> 00:03:58.633
AND CAPTION TEXT.

00:03:58.633 --> 00:04:01.533
BELOW THE TEXT, A STILL PHOTO
OF A MAN SEATED IN A WORKSHOP

00:04:01.533 --> 00:04:04.200
IS CAPTIONED "I HEARD ABOUT
THIS ARDUINO PROJECT,

00:04:04.200 --> 00:04:06.033
AND I SAW IT ONLINE."

00:04:06.033 --> 00:04:08.733
Pfeiffer: This is one
of the very simple files

00:04:08.733 --> 00:04:10.033
that we can think about.

00:04:10.033 --> 00:04:12.933
Just a marker
at the beginning of the file

00:04:12.933 --> 00:04:15.466
that identifies
the file format.

00:04:15.466 --> 00:04:20.366
The captions or subtitles--
let's call them cues--

00:04:20.366 --> 00:04:23.500
then have an individual
identifier.

00:04:23.500 --> 00:04:26.433
In this case, it's
the number one and number two.

00:04:26.433 --> 00:04:28.666
Could be any string, however.

00:04:28.666 --> 00:04:31.433
And then we've got start times
and end times

00:04:31.433 --> 00:04:32.800
on each one of these cues,

00:04:32.800 --> 00:04:35.300
and a piece of text
in there.

00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:37.566
It turns out in--

00:04:37.566 --> 00:04:40.966
as we all know how captions
are displayed on screen

00:04:40.966 --> 00:04:43.400
in something like this

00:04:43.400 --> 00:04:46.766
if it's automatically
created by the browser.

00:04:46.766 --> 00:04:49.133
Describer: THE CAPTION DISPLAYS
AT THE BOTTOM OF THE SCREEN

00:04:49.133 --> 00:04:53.066
IN WHITE LETTERING
OVER A SHADED GRAY BOX.

00:04:53.066 --> 00:04:57.766
Pfeiffer: That was the very
simplest way of doing subtitles.

00:04:57.766 --> 00:04:59.933
Now, we want to do more
than just the simple captions.

00:04:59.933 --> 00:05:03.433
In particular,
if we want to achieve

00:05:03.433 --> 00:05:04.633
all the functionality

00:05:04.633 --> 00:05:07.800
of, for example,
the CEA-608 captions,

00:05:07.800 --> 00:05:10.533
then we need to do a bit more
than just text.

00:05:10.533 --> 00:05:12.633
We also want to have
some formatting in there.

00:05:12.633 --> 00:05:15.866
Describer: ANOTHER SLIDE, TITLED
"WebVTT FORMATTED SUBTITLES,"

00:05:15.866 --> 00:05:18.800
DISPLAYS THE SAME STILL IMAGE,
WITH THE CAPTION IN GERMAN.

00:05:18.800 --> 00:05:21.966
THE WORD "ARDUINO" IS WRITTEN
IN ALL CAPS AND COLORED RED.

00:05:21.966 --> 00:05:27.700
Pfeiffer: Here is an example
on how to do bold.

00:05:27.700 --> 00:05:28.900
I'll point to it.

00:05:28.900 --> 00:05:33.133
There's a bold tag in here,
so that will be bold text.

00:05:33.133 --> 00:05:35.366
Here is some italic text.

00:05:35.366 --> 00:05:36.500
Describer: IN THE SAMPLE FILE,

00:05:36.500 --> 00:05:38.500
THE SECOND CAPTION CONTAINS
THE WORD "WOW!"

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:40.733
SURROUNDED BY THE HTML TAG
FOR BOLD,

00:05:40.733 --> 00:05:43.033
THE LETTER "b" SURROUNDED
BY ANGLED BRACKETS

00:05:43.033 --> 00:05:44.066
BEFORE THE WORD "WOW,"

00:05:44.066 --> 00:05:47.100
AND "/b" IN ANGLE BRACKETS
AFTER THE WORD "WOW."

00:05:47.100 --> 00:05:48.300
ANOTHER PHRASE IS ENCLOSED

00:05:48.300 --> 00:05:51.166
IN THE TAG FOR ITALICS,
"i" AND "/i".

00:05:51.166 --> 00:05:54.033
Pfeiffer: And up here
we've got a general way

00:05:54.033 --> 00:06:00.100
to associate style or a class
to a piece of text

00:06:00.100 --> 00:06:01.466
and give it a meaning.

00:06:01.466 --> 00:06:02.733
In this situation,

00:06:02.733 --> 00:06:06.433
we've turned a piece of text
into red text

00:06:06.433 --> 00:06:07.933
and capitalized it.

00:06:07.933 --> 00:06:09.100
Describer: THE WORD "ARDUINO"

00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:12.066
IS PRECEDED BY THE TAG
"c.red.caps"

00:06:12.066 --> 00:06:13.800
WITH A "/c" TO CLOSE.

00:06:13.800 --> 00:06:16.666
IN THE CAPTION, IT APPEARS RED
AND CAPITALIZED.

00:06:16.666 --> 00:06:20.000
Pfeiffer: Of course,
if we're using this format

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:21.466
also for subtitles,

00:06:21.466 --> 00:06:25.066
we need to be careful to cover
internationalization issues.

00:06:25.066 --> 00:06:27.600
WebVTT is very clear here.

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:30.566
It requires UTF-8
character encoding.

00:06:30.566 --> 00:06:34.233
Describer: ANOTHER SLIDE,
WebVTT FOR INTERNATIONALIZATION,

00:06:34.233 --> 00:06:36.466
ABBREVIATED
I18N.

00:06:36.466 --> 00:06:37.966
A SAMPLE CAPTION FILE CONTAINS

00:06:37.966 --> 00:06:40.133
TIME CODES FOR CAPTION
START AND STOP

00:06:40.133 --> 00:06:42.700
AND CAPTION TEXT
IN ASIAN LANGUAGE CHARACTERS.

00:06:42.700 --> 00:06:45.600
HEADINGS BELOW READ
"UTF-8 CHARACTER ENCODING"

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:46.800
"RUBY TEXT"

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:49.966
AND "VERTICAL OR HORIZONTAL
RENDERING AND ALIGNMENT."

00:06:49.966 --> 00:06:52.500
Pfeiffer: It has a ruby tag,

00:06:52.500 --> 00:06:56.866
which supports
Asian languages in particular.

00:06:56.866 --> 00:06:59.166
Describer: ANNOTATED ASIAN
LANGUAGE CHARACTERS ARE SHOWN

00:06:59.166 --> 00:07:01.166
BETWEEN AN OPEN AND CLOSE
RUBY TAG,

00:07:01.166 --> 00:07:03.633
WITH THE ANNOTATIONS
BETWEEN "rt" TAGS

00:07:03.633 --> 00:07:06.366
AND THE ANNOTATED TEXT
BETWEEN "rb" TAGS.

00:07:06.366 --> 00:07:08.033
TO THE RIGHT
OF THE START AND STOP TIMES,

00:07:08.033 --> 00:07:11.166
CODES READ "D:vertical"
AND "A:start".

00:07:11.166 --> 00:07:13.700
Pfeiffer: It also does
vertical and horizontal

00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:16.500
rendering of text.

00:07:16.500 --> 00:07:20.366
Again, possibly one of the most
important ones

00:07:20.366 --> 00:07:21.800
are Asian languages,

00:07:21.800 --> 00:07:22.966
and I think there are
a few other languages

00:07:22.966 --> 00:07:26.266
that are also
rendered vertically.

00:07:26.266 --> 00:07:29.266
And we need to make sure
we get the alignment right.

00:07:29.266 --> 00:07:34.200
Sometimes text is read
from the right to the left,

00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:36.433
so therefore it needs
to be aligned on the right

00:07:36.433 --> 00:07:37.900
rather than on the left.

00:07:37.900 --> 00:07:39.233
Describer:
ANOTHER SLIDE IS TITLED

00:07:39.233 --> 00:07:41.600
"WebVTT CAPTION POSITIONING."

00:07:41.600 --> 00:07:45.733
Pfeiffer: Now, positioning
is another requirement

00:07:45.733 --> 00:07:48.866
and, again, something
that traditional captions,

00:07:48.866 --> 00:07:51.400
TV captions,
are able to do.

00:07:51.400 --> 00:07:57.266
It's possible to position cues
anywhere in WebVTT.

00:07:57.266 --> 00:08:00.266
There are basically
three important ways

00:08:00.266 --> 00:08:01.700
to position text.

00:08:01.700 --> 00:08:04.400
Describer: A STILL SHOT FROM
"ANNIE HALL" FINDS DIANE KEATON

00:08:04.400 --> 00:08:06.500
WEARING A DRESS SHIRT,
NECKTIE, AND VEST.

00:08:06.500 --> 00:08:08.800
CAPTIONS APPEAR
IN THE CENTER OF THE VIDEO PANE

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:11.000
AT BOTH THE TOP AND BOTTOM
OF THE SCREEN.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:13.666
THE BOTTOM CAPTION TEXT
WRAPS TO A SECOND LINE.

00:08:13.666 --> 00:08:16.400
AFTER THE LINE BREAK,
THE CAPTIONS ARE CENTER ALIGNED.

00:08:16.400 --> 00:08:18.166
THE BOTTOM CAPTION READS

00:08:18.166 --> 00:08:19.866
"YEAH, I SORT OF DABBLE AROUND,
YOU KNOW."

00:08:19.866 --> 00:08:23.766
THE TOP CAPTION: "I DABBLE?
LISTEN TO ME. WHAT A JERK."

00:08:23.766 --> 00:08:26.800
HEADINGS NEXT TO THE STILL
READ "L, LINE POSITION,

00:08:26.800 --> 00:08:29.866
T, TEXT POSITION
A, ALIGNMENT."

00:08:29.866 --> 00:08:31.866
Pfeiffer: There are
line positions.

00:08:31.866 --> 00:08:38.266
So the concept of display lines
exists in WebVTT.

00:08:38.266 --> 00:08:40.600
So the line position
allows people

00:08:40.600 --> 00:08:43.666
to directly address
a specific line.

00:08:43.666 --> 00:08:49.966
It can be done with
a line number or a percentage.

00:08:49.966 --> 00:08:53.633
Then we have
the text position.

00:08:53.633 --> 00:08:57.266
This means we're placing
the text either on the left,

00:08:57.266 --> 00:09:01.366
in the middle,
or on the right.

00:09:01.366 --> 00:09:03.533
No, hold on.
That's the alignment, sorry.

00:09:03.533 --> 00:09:05.800
Alignment is
left, middle, and right.

00:09:05.800 --> 00:09:10.100
And the text position is...

00:09:10.100 --> 00:09:12.233
so when we have text
like this,

00:09:12.233 --> 00:09:16.533
it's in the middle,
and it's centered.

00:09:16.533 --> 00:09:18.100
So we can also do a centering,

00:09:18.100 --> 00:09:23.600
and we can do
a left alignment

00:09:23.600 --> 00:09:24.900
and a right alignment.

00:09:24.900 --> 00:09:28.300
But we can also move
that whole text elsewhere.

00:09:28.300 --> 00:09:30.666
So the text position
is where we move the text

00:09:30.666 --> 00:09:32.833
and the alignment is
where we align it at.

00:09:32.833 --> 00:09:34.733
Describer: A SAMPLE FILE
FEATURES POSITION CODES

00:09:34.733 --> 00:09:36.900
TO THE RIGHT
OF THE TIME CODE MARKERS.

00:09:36.900 --> 00:09:39.100
FOR THE CAPTION AT THE TOP,
THE CODES READ

00:09:39.100 --> 00:09:41.566
"A:middle" AND "L:10%".

00:09:41.566 --> 00:09:45.600
FOR THE BOTTOM CAPTION,
"A:middle" AND "L:60%".

00:09:45.600 --> 00:09:48.866
A NEW SLIDE IS TITLED
"WebVTT SPEAKER SEMANTICS."

00:09:48.866 --> 00:09:51.600
TWO FRAMES OF VIDEO FROM
THE ANIMATED PROGRAM "ARTHUR"

00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:53.900
CAPTURE A MONKEY
FROWNING AT A BUNNY.

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:56.033
THE FIRST FRAME IS CAPTIONED
"AHEM..."

00:09:56.033 --> 00:09:58.766
WITH THE CAPTION LEFT ALIGNED
TO APPEAR BELOW THE MONKEY.

00:09:58.766 --> 00:10:01.300
THE SECOND FRAME IS CAPTIONED
"WHAT'S THE MATTER?"

00:10:01.300 --> 00:10:03.466
AND IS RIGHT ALIGNED
TO APPEAR BELOW THE BUNNY.

00:10:03.466 --> 00:10:05.400
Pfeiffer: We also have
speaker semantics

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:07.000
included into WebVTT,

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.000
which is interesting
because it allows us

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:13.133
to put some semantic information
into our markup.

00:10:13.133 --> 00:10:14.200
Describer: IN THE SAMPLE FILE,

00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:16.766
TAGS APPEAR BEFORE THE TEXT
OF EACH CAPTION,

00:10:16.766 --> 00:10:19.100
"v.Beatrix"
IN THE FIRST CAPTION,

00:10:19.100 --> 00:10:20.933
AND "v.Arthur"
IN THE SECOND.

00:10:20.933 --> 00:10:22.466
THE TAGS ARE NOT CLOSED.

00:10:22.466 --> 00:10:25.300
Pfeiffer: Here, for example,
we have two people speaking.

00:10:25.300 --> 00:10:29.466
We know their position
on the left and on the right.

00:10:29.466 --> 00:10:34.133
And the speaker markup

00:10:34.133 --> 00:10:36.166
can tell us where we want
to position it

00:10:36.166 --> 00:10:39.333
and can also, for example,
help us always use

00:10:39.333 --> 00:10:42.400
the same styling
for the same speaker.

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:44.800
So, for example, we want
to use the same font,

00:10:44.800 --> 00:10:46.233
the same font color,

00:10:46.233 --> 00:10:49.500
maybe a specific outline
or something for a speaker.

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:50.766
We can define that

00:10:50.766 --> 00:10:54.133
and then apply that always
for that speaker.

00:10:54.133 --> 00:10:57.633
Describer: ANOTHER SLIDE,
WebVTT TEXT DESCRIPTIONS.

00:10:57.633 --> 00:11:00.833
Pfeiffer: Now, so much
for captions.

00:11:00.833 --> 00:11:03.233
Now we move on
to a little example

00:11:03.233 --> 00:11:05.166
on text descriptions.

00:11:05.166 --> 00:11:09.900
Here is one
that I've used previously,

00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:15.633
and we've got that
as an example on the site.

00:11:15.633 --> 00:11:18.000
Describer: A SAMPLE FILE
CONTAINS THREE DESCRIPTIONS,

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:19.933
EACH WITH THREE LINES
OF INFORMATION:

00:11:19.933 --> 00:11:22.533
DESCRIPTION NUMBER,
TIME CODE START AND STOP,

00:11:22.533 --> 00:11:24.933
AND THE TEXT TO BE READ ALOUD
BY A SCREEN READER.

00:11:24.933 --> 00:11:27.233
THE SLIDE GIVES
THREE SAMPLE DESCRIPTIONS.

00:11:27.233 --> 00:11:30.666
SAMPLE ONE, "THE ORANGE OPEN
MOVIE PROJECT PRESENTS."

00:11:30.666 --> 00:11:34.266
SAMPLE TWO, "INTRODUCTORY TITLES
ARE SHOWING ON THE BACKGROUND

00:11:34.266 --> 00:11:36.033
"OF A WATER POOL
WITH FISHES SWIMMING

