00:12:40.033 --> 00:12:43.466
TEXT BELOW THE SAMPLE READS
"NAVIGATION MARKERS."

00:12:43.466 --> 00:12:47.166
A NEW SLIDE IS TITLED
"TEXT TRACKS IN HTML5."

00:12:47.166 --> 00:12:49.066
Pfeiffer: Now, of course,
as I'm saying,

00:12:49.066 --> 00:12:51.266
controls and input
into web pages

00:12:51.266 --> 00:12:52.966
and automatic rendering,

00:12:52.966 --> 00:12:55.000
we need to know
how we're going to do that.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.600
And there is markup
in HTML5

00:12:57.600 --> 00:13:02.766
for associating captions
and formats like this

00:13:02.766 --> 00:13:04.866
with videos.

00:13:04.866 --> 00:13:10.300
In this example,
I've got all of the VTT files

00:13:10.300 --> 00:13:11.900
that we've used before.

00:13:11.900 --> 00:13:13.766
I've included them here.

00:13:13.766 --> 00:13:17.666
And what we're using for it
is called a track element,

00:13:17.666 --> 00:13:19.400
and this track element
is included

00:13:19.400 --> 00:13:23.466
underneath the video element
in the HTML5 markup.

00:13:23.466 --> 00:13:26.966
It links through
the VTT file.

00:13:26.966 --> 00:13:29.800
And there is some description
possible

00:13:29.800 --> 00:13:33.566
for the type of file it is,
so we have a label.

00:13:33.566 --> 00:13:36.333
In this case,
it's an English caption.

00:13:36.333 --> 00:13:38.733
We have a kind,
which gives us a means

00:13:38.733 --> 00:13:45.933
to group all the tracks
of the same type together.

00:13:45.933 --> 00:13:47.800
Describer: A CODE SAMPLE LISTS
A SOURCE VIDEO

00:13:47.800 --> 00:13:50.100
AND A SERIES OF TRACKS
WITH THE FOLLOWING LABELS:

00:13:50.100 --> 00:13:53.666
ENGLISH CAPTIONS, GERMAN
SUBTITLES, FRENCH SUBTITLES,

00:13:53.666 --> 00:13:56.366
ENGLISH DESCRIPTIONS,
AND CHAPTERS.

00:13:56.366 --> 00:14:00.566
EACH TRACK HAS ATTRIBUTES "KIND"
"SRC LANG" AND "SRC",

00:14:00.566 --> 00:14:04.266
WITH THE "SRC" CONTAINING
A URL TO THE WebVTT FILE.

00:14:04.266 --> 00:14:05.800
THE SAMPLE CONTAINS THE KINDS

00:14:05.800 --> 00:14:09.033
CAPTIONS, SUBTITLES,
DESCRIPTIONS, AND CHAPTERS.

00:14:09.033 --> 00:14:11.433
Pfeiffer: And we identify
the language.

00:14:11.433 --> 00:14:14.566
Because, of course, when we have
user settings in browsers,

00:14:14.566 --> 00:14:19.500
we want to automatically
make certain tracks

00:14:19.500 --> 00:14:20.833
available to the user

00:14:20.833 --> 00:14:22.533
if the user has,
for example,

00:14:22.533 --> 00:14:24.300
said that they always
want captions

00:14:24.300 --> 00:14:28.100
or they always want subtitles
in their language being shown.

00:14:28.100 --> 00:14:31.566
So the browser can
look through this markup

00:14:31.566 --> 00:14:35.666
and identify which ones
it has to turn on by default.

00:14:35.666 --> 00:14:38.600
Describer: AFTER TEXT THAT READS
"SRCLANG="

00:14:38.600 --> 00:14:40.600
THE LETTERS "EN"
ARE HIGHLIGHTED,

00:14:40.600 --> 00:14:43.166
INDICATING ENGLISH LANGUAGE.

00:14:43.166 --> 00:14:47.900
Pfeiffer: Now, in this case,
I've used only WebVTT files.

00:14:47.900 --> 00:14:54.433
The track layout, the way that
we've defined track in HTML5,

00:14:54.433 --> 00:14:56.200
is actually generic.

00:14:56.200 --> 00:14:59.400
It can be used for other types
of files as well,

00:14:59.400 --> 00:15:04.833
TTML or SRT
or any other formats

00:15:04.833 --> 00:15:07.133
that will be implemented.

00:15:07.133 --> 00:15:08.533
Describer: THE WORD "TRACK"
IS HIGHLIGHTED

00:15:08.533 --> 00:15:12.166
IN A TAG READING:
TRACK LABEL="ENGLISH CAPTIONS".

00:15:12.166 --> 00:15:14.866
Pfeiffer: But the generic way

00:15:14.866 --> 00:15:19.166
that track
works is in this way.

00:15:19.166 --> 00:15:20.633
Describer: A NEW SLIDE
IS TITLED

00:15:20.633 --> 00:15:23.000
"USING CSS FOR RICHER STYLING."

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.200
A SAMPLE FILE FEATURES
THE MAN IN HIS WORKSHOP

00:15:25.200 --> 00:15:27.800
CAPTIONED "I HEARD ABOUT
THIS ARDUINO PROJECT

00:15:27.800 --> 00:15:29.366
AND SAW IT ONLINE."

00:15:29.366 --> 00:15:31.733
THE WORD ARDUINO IS RED
AND ALL CAPS.

00:15:31.733 --> 00:15:34.766
THE REST OF THE CAPTION
IS BLACK AND MIXED TYPECASE.

00:15:34.766 --> 00:15:37.466
Pfeiffer: Now, once we've got it
in the browser,

00:15:37.466 --> 00:15:40.166
we can actually support more
than what is directly possible

00:15:40.166 --> 00:15:42.900
as markup
in the WebVTT file,

00:15:42.900 --> 00:15:45.700
because now we've got the text
in the browser,

00:15:45.700 --> 00:15:46.733
and we can make use

00:15:46.733 --> 00:15:48.866
of all the functionality
of the browser,

00:15:48.866 --> 00:15:51.700
which has styling

00:15:51.700 --> 00:15:54.100
and the concurrent style sheet
functionality

00:15:54.100 --> 00:15:55.366
available to it.

00:15:55.366 --> 00:15:58.100
So this kind of styling
is also available

00:15:58.100 --> 00:16:04.066
if used in a browser,
to these cues.

00:16:04.066 --> 00:16:09.133
And the way in which
this is being done

00:16:09.133 --> 00:16:12.133
is that there's
a pseudo-element in CSS

00:16:12.133 --> 00:16:14.533
called ::cue.

00:16:14.533 --> 00:16:16.433
And with that pseudo-element,

00:16:16.433 --> 00:16:19.200
you can address,
for example,

00:16:19.200 --> 00:16:23.333
classes in the cue markup.

00:16:23.333 --> 00:16:26.266
Describer: IN THE SAMPLE FILE,
A TAG POINTING TO ".arduino"

00:16:26.266 --> 00:16:28.000
SURROUNDS THE WORD ARDUINO.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:31.433
Pfeiffer: And you can override
the formatting

00:16:31.433 --> 00:16:34.300
that by default
would be given.

00:16:34.300 --> 00:16:35.633
You can, for example--

00:16:35.633 --> 00:16:38.166
well, in this case,
it's been turned red,

00:16:38.166 --> 00:16:41.200
uppercase,
a different font family,

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:42.733
and a lighter weight.

00:16:42.733 --> 00:16:45.300
Describer: IN A SEPARATE BOX,
UNDER THE HEADING CSS,

00:16:45.300 --> 00:16:48.400
THE ::CUE PSEUDO-ELEMENT
".arduino"

00:16:48.400 --> 00:16:50.500
CONTAINS CODE SELECTING
COLOR AS RED,

00:16:50.500 --> 00:16:52.466
TEXT-TRANSFORM AS UPPERCASE,

00:16:52.466 --> 00:16:54.400
FONT-FAMILY AS HELVETICA NEUE,

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:56.500
AND FONT-WEIGHT AS LIGHTER.

00:16:56.500 --> 00:17:00.566
A NEW SLIDE IS TITLED
"WebVTT DEFAULT RENDERING."

00:17:00.566 --> 00:17:01.866
TWO HEADINGS READ

00:17:01.866 --> 00:17:04.766
"POP-ON: BOTTOM THIRD OF VIDEO
VIEWPORT, CENTERED"

00:17:04.766 --> 00:17:08.166
AND "ROLL-UP: OVERLAPPING
CAPTIONS ARE ADDED UNDERNEATH."

00:17:08.166 --> 00:17:09.266
Pfeiffer: Now, we've
spoken a lot.

00:17:09.266 --> 00:17:11.200
We want to see a little bit
of a demo here,

00:17:11.200 --> 00:17:13.633
and I've made a little bit
of a demo

00:17:13.633 --> 00:17:17.366
which shows that we can
do more than what's typically

00:17:17.366 --> 00:17:18.933
being used for captions
right now.

00:17:18.933 --> 00:17:22.866
Most captions that are
being used are pop-on captions,

00:17:22.866 --> 00:17:25.466
which are captions
that don't overlap in time.

00:17:25.466 --> 00:17:26.900
There's one piece of caption,

00:17:26.900 --> 00:17:28.600
one cue shown;

00:17:28.600 --> 00:17:30.566
it disappears, and the next cue
is brought up.

00:17:30.566 --> 00:17:31.866
That's pop-on.

00:17:31.866 --> 00:17:36.333
And that is the default way
of rendering it.

00:17:36.333 --> 00:17:39.500
But we may have
a very different style

00:17:39.500 --> 00:17:42.366
of providing captions
as well,

00:17:42.366 --> 00:17:44.466
which has traditionally
been used

00:17:44.466 --> 00:17:47.400
mostly in live captioning.

00:17:47.400 --> 00:17:49.100
It's called roll-up.

00:17:49.100 --> 00:17:52.266
So the cues will actually
be added at the bottom

00:17:52.266 --> 00:17:54.900
and roll up as the--

00:17:54.900 --> 00:17:56.666
and the old ones
will disappear.

00:17:56.666 --> 00:17:58.266
So I've made a little example

00:17:58.266 --> 00:18:00.433
that shows how that
can be done as well.

00:18:00.433 --> 00:18:01.633
Describer: A VIDEO PLAYS.

00:18:01.633 --> 00:18:03.233
AS THE MAN IN HIS SHOP SPEAKS,

00:18:03.233 --> 00:18:04.966
TWO LINES OF LEFT-ALIGNED
CAPTIONS

00:18:04.966 --> 00:18:07.300
APPEAR TO ROLL UP
FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE SCREEN.

00:18:07.300 --> 00:18:08.633
WITH EACH NEW CAPTION,

00:18:08.633 --> 00:18:10.366
THE BOTTOM CAPTION MOVES UP
TO THE TOP LINE,

00:18:10.366 --> 00:18:12.666
AND THE TOP CAPTION DISAPPEARS.

00:18:12.666 --> 00:18:14.033
Pfeiffer: Let's hope this works.

00:18:14.033 --> 00:18:15.800
Man: I heard about
this Arduino Project,

00:18:15.800 --> 00:18:18.300
and I saw it online,
and I said, "Wow,

00:18:18.300 --> 00:18:20.233
"a lot of people are starting
to talk about this.

00:18:20.233 --> 00:18:21.666
I should check it out."

00:18:21.666 --> 00:18:24.333
Second Man: 'Cause we wanted
to make a tool

00:18:24.333 --> 00:18:27.200
for our student
that was more modern

00:18:27.200 --> 00:18:29.900
than what was available
on the market at the moment.

00:18:31.700 --> 00:18:33.133
Third Man: For me,
it was a case

00:18:33.133 --> 00:18:35.600
that this is a tool
that I could see using myself,

00:18:35.600 --> 00:18:36.966
and therefore
I could believe

00:18:36.966 --> 00:18:39.366
in actually helping to get it
out to a wider world.

00:18:39.366 --> 00:18:41.633
Fourth Man:
[speaking foreign language]

00:18:46.500 --> 00:18:48.566
Pfeiffer: So you could see

00:18:48.566 --> 00:18:51.700
that the captions
were being pushed up

00:18:51.700 --> 00:18:54.700
as they were being displayed.

00:18:54.700 --> 00:18:58.500
This is a very simple way

00:18:58.500 --> 00:19:06.333
of doing
this kind of roll-up.

00:19:06.333 --> 00:19:08.233
So as we're moving on,

00:19:08.233 --> 00:19:10.333
the next caption
gets added to the bottom.

00:19:10.333 --> 00:19:13.800
This can be improved.

00:19:13.800 --> 00:19:15.366
This is just
a very crude demo.

00:19:15.366 --> 00:19:16.566
But this can be improved

00:19:16.566 --> 00:19:18.800
with a bit more CSS
in the browser.

00:19:18.800 --> 00:19:23.800
We can, for example, transition
the text more slowly,

00:19:23.800 --> 00:19:25.800
and then it would be
more readable,

00:19:25.800 --> 00:19:28.166
rather than it
jumping there directly.

00:19:28.166 --> 00:19:31.300
There's a whole swag
of CSS functionality

00:19:31.300 --> 00:19:32.766
available to us
in the browser

00:19:32.766 --> 00:19:34.733
to make this look very nice.

00:19:34.733 --> 00:19:40.700
And the functionality is there
and possible to be used.

00:19:40.700 --> 00:19:43.666
Describer: A NEW SLIDE,
"EXOTIC: PAINT-ON CAPTIONS."

00:19:43.666 --> 00:19:48.566
Pfeiffer: I've mentioned
paint-on and roll-up captions.

00:19:48.566 --> 00:19:51.866
I've mentioned pop-on
and roll-up captions.

00:19:51.866 --> 00:19:54.766
I want to briefly also mention
paint-on captions,

00:19:54.766 --> 00:19:57.666
even though that's a bit more
of an exotic use case.

00:19:57.666 --> 00:20:02.366
But it's possible to be used
in CEA-608 captions,

00:20:02.366 --> 00:20:05.500
so we need to make sure
that it's also possible

00:20:05.500 --> 00:20:07.933
to be represented in WebVTT.

00:20:07.933 --> 00:20:10.866
And what we've introduced
for this kind of application

00:20:10.866 --> 00:20:14.100
is cue timestamps.

00:20:14.100 --> 00:20:18.466
These cue timestamps
are basically just a timestamp

00:20:18.466 --> 00:20:22.533
that is being included
into the text

00:20:22.533 --> 00:20:26.000
and says when the text
that comes afterwards

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:27.666
will be activated.

00:20:27.666 --> 00:20:29.800
Describer: A SAMPLE FILE
CONTAINS CAPTION NUMBER,

00:20:29.800 --> 00:20:31.766
CAPTION START
AND STOP TIME CODES,

00:20:31.766 --> 00:20:35.433
AND INDIVIDUAL CAPTIONED WORDS
SEPARATED BY TIMESTAMP CODES.

00:20:35.433 --> 00:20:38.866
THE TIMESTAMPS THEMSELVES
ARE ENCLOSED IN ANGLE BRACKETS.

00:20:38.866 --> 00:20:41.400
BELOW, HEADINGS READ
"CUE TIMESTAMPS"

00:20:41.400 --> 00:20:43.366
"CHARACTER RESOLUTION POSSIBLE"

00:20:43.366 --> 00:20:45.533
"STYLING THROUGH
CSS PSEUDO-SELECTORS"

00:20:45.533 --> 00:20:49.733
AND ":PAST, :FUTURE
(E.G. KARAOKE)."

00:20:49.733 --> 00:20:51.266
Pfeiffer: Here I've done it--

00:20:51.266 --> 00:20:52.633
[coughs]
pardon me--

00:20:52.633 --> 00:20:54.200
at the word level.

00:20:54.200 --> 00:20:58.833
I've put cue timestamps in
for every word,

00:20:58.833 --> 00:21:01.266
so every word would come up
one after the other

00:21:01.266 --> 00:21:02.966
on the screen.

00:21:02.966 --> 00:21:05.300
However, the resolution
is arbitrary.

00:21:05.300 --> 00:21:09.600
We could do that
on every character if necessary.

00:21:09.600 --> 00:21:11.366
Interestingly enough,

00:21:11.366 --> 00:21:15.966
that can also be used
for styling through CSS.

00:21:15.966 --> 00:21:23.000
There are the past and future
pseudo-selectors.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:26.266
And these selectors allow us,
for example,

00:21:26.266 --> 00:21:30.700
to do something like
paint the old text in yellow,

00:21:30.700 --> 00:21:32.700
the new text in white.

00:21:32.700 --> 00:21:35.533
Describer: SILVIA HIGHLIGHTS
THE ":PAST" PSEUDO-SELECTOR,

00:21:35.533 --> 00:21:38.366
THEN POINTS OUT A CODE SAMPLE
WITH THE HEADING CSS.

00:21:38.366 --> 00:21:41.366
IT CONTAINS TWO EXPRESSIONS
MAKING PAST CUE COLORS YELLOW

00:21:41.366 --> 00:21:44.333
AND ADDING A TEXT SHADOW
TO FUTURE CUES.

00:21:44.333 --> 00:21:45.866
Pfeiffer: With a text shadow,

00:21:45.866 --> 00:21:48.300
and as it goes over,
everything goes yellow.

00:21:48.300 --> 00:21:50.366
And we know this kind
of application, obviously,

00:21:50.366 --> 00:21:51.766
from karaoke,

00:21:51.766 --> 00:21:57.166
which bridges into
these applications as well,

00:21:57.166 --> 00:22:00.966
into more modern
time-aligned text applications.

00:22:00.966 --> 00:22:03.733
We can cover
all of these use cases

00:22:03.733 --> 00:22:07.466
with the same approach.

00:22:07.466 --> 00:22:11.466
So that brings me
to the end of the presentation.

00:22:11.466 --> 00:22:12.766
Describer: ANOTHER SLIDE
IS TITLED

00:22:12.766 --> 00:22:15.866
"WebVTT, A BRIDGE BETWEEN
BROADCAST AND THE WEB."

00:22:15.866 --> 00:22:19.700
POINTS BELOW READ: "FULL
FEATURES OF CEA-608 CAPTIONS"

00:22:19.700 --> 00:22:21.166
"SIMPLICITY OF EDITING"

00:22:21.166 --> 00:22:22.833
"ABILITY TO APPLY WEB STYLING"

00:22:22.833 --> 00:22:25.500
AND "OPEN AND FREELY AVAILABLE."

00:22:25.500 --> 00:22:29.833
Pfeiffer: We regard WebVTT as
a bridge between broadcast

00:22:29.833 --> 00:22:31.966
and the web of the future.

00:22:31.966 --> 00:22:37.766
We can support
all of the CEA-608 captions,

00:22:37.766 --> 00:22:39.666
all of the features,

00:22:39.666 --> 00:22:43.066
possibly also
some of the 708 features--

00:22:43.066 --> 00:22:47.433
I think most of them;
I haven't analyzed in detail.

00:22:47.433 --> 00:22:50.800
But most of the 708 features
will be supported as well.

00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:53.133
It's a simplicity
of editing,

00:22:53.133 --> 00:22:55.866
which we like
about the WebVTT format.

00:22:55.866 --> 00:22:57.966
It's readable.
You can read it here on screen.

00:22:57.966 --> 00:23:03.200
There's not too much busyness
as you're looking at it.

00:23:03.200 --> 00:23:05.366
And that means also
that it's easy to edit

00:23:05.366 --> 00:23:06.900
and to create.

00:23:06.900 --> 00:23:09.933
We have the ability
to apply web styling

00:23:09.933 --> 00:23:11.733
through the track mechanism

00:23:11.733 --> 00:23:15.066
that has been included
into HTML5.

00:23:15.066 --> 00:23:18.700
And this is an open
and freely available format.

00:23:18.700 --> 00:23:20.666
If you're looking
for references,

00:23:20.666 --> 00:23:23.300
I've put the references
on this last slide

00:23:23.300 --> 00:23:24.433
to all the specs.

00:23:24.433 --> 00:23:25.733
They're available for free.

00:23:25.733 --> 00:23:27.566
Thank you very much.

