00:23:43.333 --> 00:23:44.833
But please, if you have
any questions for Silvia

00:23:44.833 --> 00:23:48.933
about WebVTT,
please step up to the mic.

00:23:48.933 --> 00:23:50.766
Pfeiffer: I was going
very quickly,

00:23:50.766 --> 00:23:52.266
so if somebody wants
to go back

00:23:52.266 --> 00:23:55.066
and explore any of the features
in more detail,

00:23:55.066 --> 00:23:57.833
this is probably
the opportunity.

00:23:57.833 --> 00:23:59.633
Steinberg: Hi,
I'm Daniel Steinberg at Google.

00:23:59.633 --> 00:24:01.566
A couple questions.

00:24:01.566 --> 00:24:05.266
When you had the line number
specification,

00:24:05.266 --> 00:24:10.000
how does that apply
when you have vertical text?

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:12.700
Pfeiffer:
Let me just find that.

00:24:12.700 --> 00:24:13.733
Here, this one?

00:24:13.733 --> 00:24:14.666
Steinberg: Yeah.

00:24:14.666 --> 00:24:17.033
Describer: SILVIA CUES
THE "CAPTION POSITION" SLIDE

00:24:17.033 --> 00:24:19.266
THAT HIGHLIGHTS LINE POSITION,
TEXT POSITION,

00:24:19.266 --> 00:24:20.933
AND ALIGNMENT FEATURES.

00:24:20.933 --> 00:24:26.100
Pfeiffer: So the line numbers
are basically done in--

00:24:26.100 --> 00:24:27.166
for horizontal text,

00:24:27.166 --> 00:24:29.266
obviously from the top
to the bottom.

00:24:29.266 --> 00:24:32.800
And for vertical text,
they are turned around.

00:24:32.800 --> 00:24:35.466
So they apply in the same way.

00:24:35.466 --> 00:24:40.966
Steinberg: Okay, and you have
a lot of the underpinnings

00:24:40.966 --> 00:24:44.200
for interactive text,
but not the actual--

00:24:44.200 --> 00:24:45.833
I didn't see anything
actually there.

00:24:45.833 --> 00:24:49.233
So the ability to say
this particular tag is live,

00:24:49.233 --> 00:24:52.066
and clicking on it might give
a link or something like that.

00:24:52.066 --> 00:24:54.866
Have you considered
interactivity?

00:24:54.866 --> 00:24:56.566
Pfeiffer: Interactivity--

00:24:56.566 --> 00:25:00.500
you particularly talking
about hyperlinks in this case?

00:25:00.500 --> 00:25:01.700
Steinberg:
In this case, yes.

00:25:01.700 --> 00:25:02.700
Pfeiffer: Yes, so hyperlinks

00:25:02.700 --> 00:25:05.733
is something of a bit
of a controversial issue.

00:25:05.733 --> 00:25:07.466
We've discussed this.

00:25:07.466 --> 00:25:10.866
It is obviously something
that can easily be added.

00:25:10.866 --> 00:25:12.766
We've got the markup
in HTML5.

00:25:12.766 --> 00:25:18.433
We could easily put a "a" tag
in there and a hyperlink.

00:25:18.433 --> 00:25:21.366
It's not something
that's currently part

00:25:21.366 --> 00:25:26.500
of the specification simply
because people don't believe

00:25:26.500 --> 00:25:28.066
that it's a very good
experience.

00:25:28.066 --> 00:25:30.466
When you're watching captions,
they stay on the screen

00:25:30.466 --> 00:25:32.000
only for a very short
amount of time.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.500
By the time you've decided
that you want to follow a link,

00:25:34.500 --> 00:25:35.766
it's already gone.

00:25:35.766 --> 00:25:37.533
That's the reason.

00:25:37.533 --> 00:25:41.100
So I'm obviously not fully
subscribed to that reason.

00:25:41.100 --> 00:25:44.300
I would actually like to have
hyperlinks in it as well.

00:25:44.300 --> 00:25:48.500
What I look at in this format
is that it's easy to extend it,

00:25:48.500 --> 00:25:50.966
and if somebody
was to support it,

00:25:50.966 --> 00:25:54.933
then it is not a problem
to put that in as well.

00:25:54.933 --> 00:25:57.166
Steinberg: Yeah, something
to consider with the hyperlinks

00:25:57.166 --> 00:25:59.366
is that, because
you have the ability

00:25:59.366 --> 00:26:02.633
to author
different kinds of files,

00:26:02.633 --> 00:26:05.100
you could have a description
that had a longer time

00:26:05.100 --> 00:26:06.433
and had a longer duration.

00:26:06.433 --> 00:26:08.200
It wouldn't
have to disappear

00:26:08.200 --> 00:26:10.733
when a caption line
disappeared.

00:26:10.733 --> 00:26:13.033
Pfeiffer: In fact,
I should actually add something.

00:26:13.033 --> 00:26:17.800
We've got, as I mentioned,
we've got kinds of text

00:26:17.800 --> 00:26:21.600
that we're expecting
in a WebVTT file.

00:26:21.600 --> 00:26:23.866
I've talked about
captions and subtitles,

00:26:23.866 --> 00:26:25.733
I've talked about
text descriptions,

00:26:25.733 --> 00:26:27.133
and I've talked about
navigation.

00:26:27.133 --> 00:26:28.866
I've only mentioned metadata,

00:26:28.866 --> 00:26:31.066
but metadata actually
solves that problem.

00:26:31.066 --> 00:26:33.833
Metadata means that

00:26:33.833 --> 00:26:36.500
you're allowed to put anything
into a cue:

00:26:36.500 --> 00:26:38.133
any markup you want,

00:26:38.133 --> 00:26:39.633
any non-markup you want,

00:26:39.633 --> 00:26:41.400
any text, anything at all.

00:26:41.400 --> 00:26:44.500
It just means that the browser
can't do anything with it.

00:26:44.500 --> 00:26:48.100
It decides--it sees that
it's of the kind "metadata"

00:26:48.100 --> 00:26:49.600
and goes,
"I'm being hands-off.

00:26:49.600 --> 00:26:52.466
"I'm just gonna hand it on
to the JavaScript,

00:26:52.466 --> 00:26:54.866
and the JavaScript can do
with it whatever it likes."

00:26:54.866 --> 00:26:57.200
So this would be one way
to have interactivity in it.

00:26:57.200 --> 00:26:59.900
You could just
grab it through JavaScript

00:26:59.900 --> 00:27:04.466
and then put it into a div
on your page,

00:27:04.466 --> 00:27:07.800
and then there would be
a hyperlink.

00:27:07.800 --> 00:27:10.200
And anything else
that you can come up with

00:27:10.200 --> 00:27:14.166
that's time-aligned would
work in a similar way as well.

00:27:14.166 --> 00:27:15.200
Steinberg:
And one last question.

00:27:15.200 --> 00:27:17.033
You showed
the different formats--

00:27:17.033 --> 00:27:19.533
captions and descriptions
and whatnot--

00:27:19.533 --> 00:27:22.933
as essentially the same
VTT format,

00:27:22.933 --> 00:27:26.933
distinguished only
by the track tag.

00:27:26.933 --> 00:27:31.300
And I wonder if there's
enough semantic difference

00:27:31.300 --> 00:27:35.166
that you'd want to be able to
distinguish it in another way.

00:27:35.166 --> 00:27:36.500
Like, for instance,
would you build a--

00:27:36.500 --> 00:27:37.700
could you build a file

00:27:37.700 --> 00:27:40.633
that had captions
and descriptions in it?

00:27:40.633 --> 00:27:46.700
Or might you want to have
some identifier in the file say,

00:27:46.700 --> 00:27:48.233
"This is a description file,"

00:27:48.233 --> 00:27:51.966
rather than count on
the track tag?

00:27:51.966 --> 00:27:56.200
Pfeiffer: Mixing content
in one track

00:27:56.200 --> 00:27:58.766
is of course possible.

00:27:58.766 --> 00:28:02.900
Like, you could concatenate,
for example,

00:28:02.900 --> 00:28:09.033
a caption file with
an audio description file.

00:28:09.033 --> 00:28:12.066
Then you would basically
have two tracks available

00:28:12.066 --> 00:28:13.566
through one file.

00:28:13.566 --> 00:28:17.933
It's not a very easy way
to deal with,

00:28:17.933 --> 00:28:21.566
and it would require a lot
of additional implementation.

00:28:21.566 --> 00:28:23.033
So, for example,

00:28:23.033 --> 00:28:27.566
if that concatenated case
was to be handled,

00:28:27.566 --> 00:28:29.433
the browsers
would need to find out

00:28:29.433 --> 00:28:31.600
where the second file starts
and so on.

00:28:31.600 --> 00:28:35.566
We actually like to keep
the semantics separate.

00:28:35.566 --> 00:28:39.933
And HTML markup is built
on keeping semantics separate.

00:28:39.933 --> 00:28:42.633
So this is why we introduced
the "kind" attribute.

00:28:42.633 --> 00:28:45.000
And so therefore,
in one file,

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:47.800
you will only find captions
of one type.

00:28:50.333 --> 00:28:52.866
Thank you.

00:28:52.866 --> 00:28:53.966
Foliot: Hi, Silvia.

00:28:53.966 --> 00:28:56.033
John Foliot
from Stanford University.

00:28:56.033 --> 00:28:59.233
When you gave
the code example of the CSS,

00:28:59.233 --> 00:29:01.300
it's not clear where
the CSS actually lives.

00:29:01.300 --> 00:29:04.100
Is it embedded
in the WebVTT file?

00:29:04.100 --> 00:29:06.733
Can you have an external file
and link it?

00:29:06.733 --> 00:29:10.200
Can you just maybe get into that
a little bit further?

00:29:10.200 --> 00:29:12.566
Pfeiffer: Yeah, let me
just find it. Sorry.

00:29:12.566 --> 00:29:17.766
So I've deliberately just
put that there as a snippet,

00:29:17.766 --> 00:29:19.966
because it actually
doesn't matter where it lives.

00:29:19.966 --> 00:29:21.133
Describer: SYLVIA PULLS UP

00:29:21.133 --> 00:29:23.366
THE "USING CSS
FOR RICHER STYLING" PAGE,

00:29:23.366 --> 00:29:25.666
WITH THE ::CSS PSEUDO-ELEMENT

00:29:25.666 --> 00:29:28.766
IN A SEPARATE TEXT BOX
FROM THE WebVTT FILE.

00:29:28.766 --> 00:29:32.800
Pfeiffer: At the moment,
because we're doing the CSS

00:29:32.800 --> 00:29:35.300
through the HTML page,

00:29:35.300 --> 00:29:38.833
that includes
this file up there...

00:29:38.833 --> 00:29:42.800
that HTML page could
either have this CSS piece

00:29:42.800 --> 00:29:46.300
directly in the HTML page
and address it--

00:29:46.300 --> 00:29:48.033
so an in-band CSS.

00:29:48.033 --> 00:29:50.500
Or it could be in
an external CSS file

00:29:50.500 --> 00:29:54.300
and be pulled into
the HTML page

00:29:54.300 --> 00:29:57.000
together with
the WebVTT file.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:29:58.966
Foliot: So it always sits
outside of the VTT file.

00:29:58.966 --> 00:30:00.400
Pfeiffer: It can.
Yeah, well...

00:30:00.400 --> 00:30:03.000
So we're currently
under discussion

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:04.233
whether this
is a functionality

00:30:04.233 --> 00:30:06.966
that we'd want to add
to WebVTT as well.

00:30:06.966 --> 00:30:10.966
So whether you want
a WebVTT file

00:30:10.966 --> 00:30:13.533
that links
to a style sheet.

00:30:13.533 --> 00:30:17.733
We're careful about that
because we--

00:30:17.733 --> 00:30:21.733
this comes from
a very web point of view.

00:30:21.733 --> 00:30:24.500
We don't really want to pollute
the WebVTT file

00:30:24.500 --> 00:30:26.866
with this web functionality,

00:30:26.866 --> 00:30:30.100
because there are applications
outside the web browser

00:30:30.100 --> 00:30:32.300
that do not want to have
to implement,

00:30:32.300 --> 00:30:34.300
for example,
all of CSS style sheets

00:30:34.300 --> 00:30:36.400
in order to display
captions properly.

00:30:36.400 --> 00:30:37.966
So it probably
makes more sense

00:30:37.966 --> 00:30:39.866
to have this
as a separate file.

00:30:39.866 --> 00:30:42.800
And if people do want to have
this additional functionality,

00:30:42.800 --> 00:30:44.966
they can use
the WebVTT file

00:30:44.966 --> 00:30:47.100
and the CSS file together

00:30:47.100 --> 00:30:52.500
and parse them, and use them
in their style sheet engine

00:30:52.500 --> 00:30:57.500
to come up
with the proper display.

00:30:57.500 --> 00:30:59.733
Black: I actually,
I have a practical example

00:30:59.733 --> 00:31:01.266
of why you would want
the CSS.

00:31:01.266 --> 00:31:02.300
Is this on?
Can you hear me?

00:31:02.300 --> 00:31:03.333
Pfeiffer: Yes.

00:31:03.333 --> 00:31:04.700
Black: I have
a practical example

00:31:04.700 --> 00:31:06.900
of why you would want
the CSS to be outside the VTT.

00:31:06.900 --> 00:31:09.500
I work currently with people
who are producing caption files

00:31:09.500 --> 00:31:11.066
for the UK market

00:31:11.066 --> 00:31:13.933
and who are then redistributing
that same video here in the US,

00:31:13.933 --> 00:31:16.566
and they have to basically
redo the entire caption file

00:31:16.566 --> 00:31:19.133
because UK audiences
are expecting, for instance,

00:31:19.133 --> 00:31:22.500
to see a particular speaker
marked up in a particular color.

00:31:22.500 --> 00:31:24.400
Here in the US,
we're not expecting that.

00:31:24.400 --> 00:31:26.633
So you could imagine
if you had one format

00:31:26.633 --> 00:31:28.966
where you marked up
the content semantically

00:31:28.966 --> 00:31:31.666
that, depending on whether
you showed it in a player

00:31:31.666 --> 00:31:34.100
here for the US
or there for the UK

00:31:34.100 --> 00:31:35.433
with the same caption file,

00:31:35.433 --> 00:31:36.966
you could display it
differently

00:31:36.966 --> 00:31:39.266
according to different users'
regional preferences.

00:31:39.266 --> 00:31:41.733
Foliot: I would also add
that user style sheets,

00:31:41.733 --> 00:31:44.133
the user could actually
increase the font size

00:31:44.133 --> 00:31:46.700
to their
specific requirements.

00:31:46.700 --> 00:31:47.833
Pfeiffer: Yes.

00:31:47.833 --> 00:31:49.233
Foliot: A second,
really minor question.

00:31:49.233 --> 00:31:50.466
On the alignment,

00:31:50.466 --> 00:31:53.733
you said it could be
left, right, or--

00:31:53.733 --> 00:31:55.033
was it
middle or center?

00:31:55.033 --> 00:31:57.766
Can you actually
have it justified as well?

00:32:00.766 --> 00:32:02.166
Pfeiffer: No.

00:32:02.166 --> 00:32:05.666
I don't think we have
a means to justify the text.

00:32:05.666 --> 00:32:08.733
But I also think that,
actually--

00:32:08.733 --> 00:32:14.433
so from all the quality captions
literature that I've read,

00:32:14.433 --> 00:32:15.733
how to do quality captions,

00:32:15.733 --> 00:32:20.266
I think justification
has never been proposed

00:32:20.266 --> 00:32:22.533
as a readable way
of doing it

00:32:22.533 --> 00:32:26.533
because it changes
the spacing between characters

00:32:26.533 --> 00:32:28.700
and so therefore makes the text
actually harder to read.

00:32:28.700 --> 00:32:30.133
Foliot: I agree.

00:32:30.133 --> 00:32:32.033
Pfeiffer: I don't think we
actually need that feature.

00:32:32.033 --> 00:32:34.100
But it is
a good point, yeah.

00:32:34.100 --> 00:32:35.766
Foliot: Well, it just wasn't
specifically declared

00:32:35.766 --> 00:32:36.766
one way or the other.

00:32:36.766 --> 00:32:37.766
I agree with you.

00:32:37.766 --> 00:32:39.066
Pfeiffer: Yeah, okay, fine.

00:32:39.066 --> 00:32:41.466
Excellent.

